refsect1.para:
     each is typically used in conjunction with
     list to traverse an array; for instance,
     $HTTP_POST_VARS:


       Traversing $HTTP_POST_VARS with
       each



echo "Values submitted via POST method:<br>";
reset ($HTTP_POST_VARS);
while (list ($key, $val) = each ($HTTP_POST_VARS)) {
    echo "$key => $val<br>";
}

Searches haystack for
needle and returns &true;
if it is found in the array, &false; otherwise.

example.programlisting:
$os = array ("Mac", "NT", "Irix", "Linux");
if (in_array ("Irix", $os)) {
    print "Got Irix";
}
if (in_array ("mac", $os)) {
    print "Got mac";
}

refsect1.para:
     Sorts an array by key in reverse order, maintaining key to data
     correlations. This is useful mainly for associative arrays.

      krsort example


$fruits = array ("d"=>"lemon", "a"=>"orange", "b"=>"banana", "c"=>"apple");
krsort ($fruits);
reset ($fruits);
while (list ($key, $val) = each ($fruits)) {
    echo "$key = $val\n";
}

     Sorts an array by key, maintaining key to data correlations. This
     is useful mainly for associative arrays.

      ksort example


$fruits = array ("d"=>"lemon", "a"=>"orange", "b"=>"banana", "c"=>"apple");
ksort ($fruits);
reset ($fruits);
while (list ($key, $val) = each ($fruits)) {
    echo "$key = $val\n";
}

example.programlisting:
$array1 = $array2 = array ("img12.png", "img10.png", "img2.png", "img1.png");

sort($array1);
echo "Standard sorting\n";
print_r($array1);

natsort($array2);
echo "\nNatural order sorting\n";
print_r($array2);

refsect1.para:
See also
end, next,
prev, and reset.

example.programlisting:
foreach(range(0, 9) as $number) {
    echo $number;
}
foreach(range('a', 'z') as $letter) {
    echo $letter;
}
foreach(range('z', 'a') as $letter) {
    echo $letter;
}

# array_reverse can be used to flip the order of a range
foreach(array_reverse(range(0,9)) as $number) {
    echo $number;
}

# array_map() can be used to turn integers into characters using chr()
foreach(array_map('chr', range(ord('a'),ord('z'))) as $character) {
    echo $character;
}

refsect1.para:
     This function sorts an array in reverse order (highest to lowest).

      rsort example


$fruits = array ("lemon", "orange", "banana", "apple");
rsort ($fruits);
reset ($fruits);
while (list ($key, $val) = each ($fruits)) {
    echo "$key = $val\n";
}

     This function shuffles (randomizes the order of the elements in)
     an array. You must use srand to seed this
     function.

      shuffle example


$numbers = range (1,20);
srand ((float)microtime()*1000000);
shuffle ($numbers);
while (list (, $number) = each ($numbers)) {
    echo "$number ";
}

     This function sorts an array.  Elements will be arranged from
     lowest to highest when this function has completed.

      sort example


<?php

$fruits = array ("lemon", "orange", "banana", "apple");
sort ($fruits);
reset ($fruits);
while (list ($key, $val) = each ($fruits)) {
    echo "fruits[".$key."] = ".$val."\n";
}

?>

refentry.refsect1:
    Description

      voiduksort
      arrayarray
      functioncmp_function



     This function will sort the keys of an array using a
     user-supplied comparison function.  If the array you wish to sort
     needs to be sorted by some non-trivial criteria, you should use
     this function.


     uksort example


function cmp ($a, $b) {
    if ($a == $b) return 0;
    return ($a > $b) ? -1 : 1;
}

$a = array (4 => "four", 3 => "three", 20 => "twenty", 10 => "ten");

uksort ($a, "cmp");

while (list ($key, $value) = each ($a)) {
    echo "$key: $value\n";
}





     This example would display:





20: twenty
10: ten
4: four
3: three



    &note.func-callback;


     See also usort, uasort,
     sort, asort,
     arsort, ksort,
     natsort, and rsort.

    Description

      voidusort
      arrayarray
      stringcmp_function



     This function will sort an array by its values using a
     user-supplied comparison function.  If the array you wish to sort
     needs to be sorted by some non-trivial criteria, you should use
     this function.



     The comparison function must return an integer less than, equal
     to, or greater than zero if the first argument is considered to
     be respectively less than, equal to, or greater than the
     second. If two members compare as equal, their order in the
     sorted array is undefined.




      usort example


function cmp ($a, $b) {
    if ($a == $b) return 0;
    return ($a > $b) ? -1 : 1;
}

$a = array (3, 2, 5, 6, 1);

usort ($a, "cmp");

while (list ($key, $value) = each ($a)) {
    echo "$key: $value\n";
}






     This example would display:





0: 6
1: 5
2: 3
3: 2
4: 1






      Obviously in this trivial case the rsort
      function would be more appropriate.






       usort example using multi-dimensional array



function cmp ($a, $b) {
    return strcmp($a["fruit"], $b["fruit"]);
}

$fruits[0]["fruit"] = "lemons";
$fruits[1]["fruit"] = "apples";
$fruits[2]["fruit"] = "grapes";

usort($fruits, "cmp");

while (list ($key, $value) = each ($fruits)) {
    echo "\$fruits[$key]: " . $value["fruit"] . "\n";
}






     When sorting a multi-dimensional array, $a and $b contain
     references to the first index of the array.



     This example would display:





$fruits[0]: apples
$fruits[1]: grapes
$fruits[2]: lemons



    &note.func-callback;




       usort example using a member function of an object



class TestObj {
    var $name;

    function TestObj($name)
    {
        $this->name = $name;
    }

    /* This is the static comparing function: */
    function cmp_obj($a, $b)
    {
        $al = strtolower($a->name);
        $bl = strtolower($b->name);
        if ($al == $bl) return 0;
        return ($al > $bl) ? +1 : -1;
    }
}

$a[] = new TestObj("c");
$a[] = new TestObj("b");
$a[] = new TestObj("d");

uasort($a, array ("TestObj", "cmp_obj"));

foreach ($a as $item) {
    print $item->name."\n";
}






     This example would display:




b
c
d





      The underlying quicksort function in some C libraries (such as
      on Solaris systems) may cause PHP to crash if the comparison
      function does not return consistent values.




     See also uasort,
     uksort, sort,
     asort,
     arsort,ksort,
     natsort, and rsort.
